Motor Trend Cars Mileage Analysis

Introduction

This is an analysis prepared for Motor Trend, an automobile industry publication. The purpose of our analysis is to explore the relationship between fuel consumption and automobile design - and performance - for a set of 1973-1974 models. In particular, we are looking to:

  • Determine whether an automatic or manual transmission is better for MPG
  • Quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions

Motor Trend Data

A series of road tests were performed by Motor Trend in which gas mileage and other design and performance attributes were recorded for automobile models. The dataset to be used in our analysis is an extract of road tests published in the March, April, June and July issues of the 1974 edition of the magazine. We begin by loading our dataset and reviewing its structure.

data(mtcars)
str(mtcars)

Our dataset includes 11 variables for a total of 32 models of automobiles. The following is a more detailed description of the variables:

Variable Description Type
mpg Fuel Consumption (Miles per gallon) Continuous
cyl Number of cylinders Discrete
disp Cyl displacement (i.e.Engine Size)(cubic inch) Continuous
hp Horsepower Continuous
drat Final Drive Ratio Continuous
wt Weight (thousand pounds) Continuous
qsec Quarter mile time (Seconds) Continuous
vs Engine Shape Discrete (V = 0, Straight = 1)
am Transmission Type Discrete (Auto = 0, Manual = 1)
gear Number of Transmission Speeds Discrete
carb Number of Carboretur Barrels Discrete

Of particular interest to our analysis in the onset is the mpg variable representing fuel consumption. Also, the am variable representing transmission type.

Analysis of Fuel Consumption

Fig.1 is a histogram of fuel consumption (mpg) for our population of automobiles. The distribution has a mean of 20.090625 and standard deviation of 6.0269481. The distribution may be skewed slightly to the left. Overall, it appears to be normal though.

# plot histogram
qplot(mpg,data=mtcars, geom="blank")+ 
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),binwidth = 5)+

Fuel Consumption By Transmission Type

We begin by looking at what the population is for each type of transmission. Fig. 2a is a count of automobile models by transmission type. There is a higher incidence of models with automatic versus manual transmissions. This is in line with expectation as there has been a shift away from manual transmissions in the U.S. Since we are interested in how transmissions affect fuel consumption, we next look at their relationship. Fig. 2b is a plot of miles per gallon by transmission type. Our figure shows manual transmissions on average have higher miles per gallon, which translate into greater fuel efficiency. It is a common perceptions that manual transmissions are more fuel efficient, and our initial observations seem to support that perception. However, further testing is needed to confirm that there is a difference in fuel consumption between the types of transmissions.

# plot number of models by transmission type
plot1 <- qplot(x = factor(am,labels = c("Auto","Manual")),data = mtcars, geom="bar", 
               main = "Fig. 2a", xlab = "Trans Type")

# plot miles per gallon by transmission type
plot2 <- qplot(x = factor(am,labels = c("Auto","Manual")), y = mpg, data = mtcars, 
               geom = "boxplot", main = "Fig. 2b", xlab = "Trans Type")

# put plots side by side
grid.arrange(plot1,plot2,nrow = 1, ncol = 2)

Test of Two Transmission Types

Fig. 2b shows manual transmissions have a higher fuel efficiency on average than automatic transmissions. To determine whether this difference is statistically significant, we subset our dataset into two sets based on transmission type and use a Students t-Test to the hypotheses:

  • H0 = 0 no difference between transmission types
  • Ha <> 0 a difference exists between transmission types

We assume a 95% confidence level (|p| > 0.05), and the variances for the two sets are not equal.

mt <- with(mtcars,t.test(mpg[am==0],mpg[am==1]))
print(mt)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mpg[am == 0] and mpg[am == 1]
## t = -3.7671, df = 18.332, p-value = 0.001374
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.280194  -3.209684
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  17.14737  24.39231

The p-value from our test, 0.0013736, is significant with a 95% confidence level. We therefore fail to reject the alternate hypothesis (Ha). In conclusion, the difference between both automatic and manual transmissions with regard to fuel consumption appears to hold true.

Quantifying Fuel Consumption Differences Between Transmission Types

Our analysis next attempts to quantify the differences in fuel consumption by transmission type using a linear regression model, which explains the relationship between fuel consumption and transmission type.

Simple Linear Regression

We begin with a simple linear regression model using fuel consumption, mpg, as the dependent variable and transmission type, am, as our independent variable. A 95% confidence level (|p| < 0.05) is assumed for our model.

# simple linear regression of mpg vs transmission
fit <- lm(mpg ~ factor(am), mtcars)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ factor(am), data = mtcars)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -9.3923 -3.0923 -0.2974  3.2439  9.5077 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value            Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   17.147      1.125  15.247 0.00000000000000113 ***
## factor(am)1    7.245      1.764   4.106            0.000285 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.902 on 30 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3598, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3385 
## F-statistic: 16.86 on 1 and 30 DF,  p-value: 0.000285

The independent variable, am, has a p-value of 0.000285. Therefore, the variable am considered to be significant, with a 95% confidence level, in explaining the relationship. However, the percentage of total variability explained by our linear model is low at 0.3597989. Confounding variables may need to be considered in the relationship.

Multivariate Linear Regression

We attempt a multivariate model that includes all variables of model design and performance in our dataset. Again, we assume a 95% confidence level (|p| > 0.05).

# all variables
fit2 <- lm(mpg~., mtcars)
summary(fit2)

The percentage of total variability now explained by our linear relationship is 0.8690158, an improvement over the simple linear regression model. However, the p-value of 9 of our dependent variables exceed our 95% confidence level, indicating there is not a significant relationship with fuel consumption. We observe the variable wt is shown to be significant.

Other variables to consider in a model are qsec and hp. However, as expected, these two variables are highly correlated.

cor(mtcars$qsec,mtcars$hp)
## [1] -0.7082234

It is assumed horsepower would an affect the quarter mile time for an automobile. Therefore, we choose to omit hp from our model, since qsec was shown to have a more significant relationship with fuel consumption. Through model testing, we confirm the omission of hp is appropriate (see Appendix, Analysis of Variance). The result is a model with mpg as the dependent outcome, and the independent predictors am, wt, and qsec. We apply our model, assuming a 95% confidence level (|p| < 0.05).

fit3 <- lm(mpg~am+wt+qsec, data = mtcars)
summary(fit3)

The percentage of total variability now explained by the linear relationship is 0.8496636. Further, the p-values of 3 independent predictors indicate a significant relationship with fuel consumption. We confirm this is indeed the most appropriate model (See Appendix, Stepwise Regression and Appendix, Model Diagnostics). Our final model shows that there is a 2.9358372 mpg difference between automatic and manual transmissions.

Analysis of Variance

To evaluate whether to include the hp in our model, we perform a nested test using Analysis of Variance (anova). We assume a 95% confidence level (|F| < 0.05). Our test shows the addition of hp in our model is not significant in explaining the relationship with fuel consumption.

fit.a <- lm(mpg~am+wt+qsec,mtcars)
fit.b <- lm(mpg~am+wt+qsec+hp,mtcars)
anova(fit.a,fit.b)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: mpg ~ am + wt + qsec
## Model 2: mpg ~ am + wt + qsec + hp
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1     28 169.29                           
## 2     27 160.07  1    9.2195 1.5551 0.2231

Model Diagnostics

We run the diagnostic plots for our selected model to evaluate the residuals, and for influence and high leverage observations.

  • Residuals vs.Fitted: Plot to show if residuals have a non-linear relationship. Review of our plot shows a slight non-linear relationship as the plotted line appears to curve. Overall, the plotted residuals do not show a systematic pattern or signs of heteroskedasticity though.

  • Normal Q-Q: Plot to show if residuals are normally distributed. Review of our plot appears to indicate normality as our residuals fall roughly on the plotted line.

  • Scale-Location: Plot to show if residuals are spread equally along ranges of predictors. Our plot shows a slightly horizontal line, indicating the spread of variance may be equal across our range (homoscedastic). However, we note the line is trending towards vertical.

  • Residuals vs.Leverage: Plot to show if there are any influential observations. Our plot shows no signs of influential observations as all observations are within Cooks distance lines.

In conclusion, we do not see any significant systematic patterns, or highly influential or leveraged observations, that would cause us to dismiss the selected model.
